        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>450 W. Randolph St.<lb/>
                Chicago&#44; Dec. 22. 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/>
                Dear friend&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Your essay on &#34;the Jews in Italy&#34; I have read with<lb/> an interest growing while reading it.  It has only one<lb/> great fault&#58; it is too short&#44; and therefore omits much what<lb/> ought to have been stated.  Especially happy&#44; it seems to me&#44;<lb/> you have been in your lucid exposition of the characteristic<lb/> differences between Italian Judaism and German&#45;Polish Judaism<lb/> in the centuries preceding the times of N. H. Wessely.<lb/></p>
            <p>Permit me to call your attention to one small in&#45;<lb/>accuracy.  Speaking of Nathan ben Ye&#39;hiel you mention<lb/> &#34;Rashi of the next century.&#34;  But Rashi was not of the<lb/> <hi rend="underline">next</hi> century&#44; he was of the <hi rend="underline">same</hi> century with Nathan&#44;&#45;&#45;both<lb/> were contemporaries.<lb/></p>
            <p>In the notes to your essay you refer to articles of yours<lb/> in the &#34;Jewish Messenger&#34; and in the periodicals.  It is a<lb/> pity that such articles are scattered in <sic>ephemerial</sic> papers<lb/> and become so difficult of access after some time.  For<lb/> you know that there are very few who care to collect and<lb/> to preserve the numbers of our Jewish weeklies.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I conclude with expressing the wish that you and<lb/> yours may enjoy the best of health&#44; and that you<lb/> may often favor American Israel with learned and in&#45;<lb/>structive papers.<lb/>  Yours very sincerely<lb/> B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
